04385nam a22006495i 9780271071756DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211996pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710717567 a10.1515/97802710717562doi  a(DE-B1597)583652  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN71b.S743 1997 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a701.12201 aStecker, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArtworks :bMeaning, Definition, Value /cRobert Stecker. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (334 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. DEFINITION -- t1. WHY WE SHOULD LOOK FOR A DEFINITION OF ART -- t2. SIMPLE FUNCTIONALISM AND FUNCTIONALISM PER SE -- t3. HISTORICAL FUNCTIONALISM, OR THE FOUR-FACTOR THEORY -- t4. INSTITUTIONAL DEFINITIONS -- t5. HISTORICAL DEFINITIONS -- tPART II. MEANING -- t6. OVERVIEW -- t7. INCOMPATIBLE INTERPRETATIONS -- t8. CRITICAL MONISM AND CRITICAL PLURALISM: How to Have Both -- t9. MEANING AND INTERPRETATION: The Role of Intention and Convention -- t10. HYPOTHETICAL INTENTIONS AND IMPLIED AUTHORS -- t11. PRAGMATISM AND INTERPRETATION -- tPART III. VALUE -- t12. ARTISTIC VALUE -- t13. THE VALUE OF LITERATURE -- tCONCLUSION -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is art? What is it to understand a work of art? What is the value of art? Robert Stecker seeks to answer these central questions of aesthetics by placing them within the context of an ongoing debate criticizing, but also explaining what can be learned from, alternative views. His unified philosophy of art, defined in terms of its evolving functions, is used to explain and to justify current interpretive practices and to motivate an investigation of artistic value.Stecker defines art (roughly) as an item that is an artwork at time t if and only if it is in one of the central art forms at t and is intended to fulfill a function art has at t, or it is an artifact that achieves excellence in fulfilling such a function. Further, he sees the standard of acceptability for interpretations of artworks to be relative to their aim. Finally, he tries to understand the value of artworks through an analysis of literature and the identification of the most important functions of literary works.In addition to offering original answers to major questions of aesthetics, Artworks covers most of the major issues in contemporary analytic aesthetics and discusses many major, as well as many minor, figures who have written about these issues, including Stanley Fish, Joseph Margolis, Richard Rorty, and Richard Shusterman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArt appreciation. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271071756zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271071756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271071756.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK